The offices also include a nursery, the architects understood
The administrative building of Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to hide a mini-school with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be attended by children of Arch.Design employees.
The design-architectural company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important buildings in Brno, has been counting on space for its corporate mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
She employs nearly 90 people, mostly at the age of baby boom, and she cared about allowing women designers and architects to get back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of short-time work, the nursery is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees within the social program.
Thus, builders and architects have the opportunity to combine demanding employment with the care of a child.
The mini-school was invented by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (a grant of 2, 8 million. CZK) could purchase equipment and equipment and for two years provide qualified personnel and operation.
After exhaustion of the financial subsidy (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to run a mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year and Economy Rating significantly helped with the application for the subsidy.
Care is provided by qualified staff, children are taken care of by a nurse and a kindergarten teacher all day, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are over 3 years old.
Because it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day there are more.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the programmatic content in the mini-school is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but also provide quality teaching - from basic cognition to preparation for school benches, English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of young children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and avoid stressful situations with delayed pick-up of children from kindergartens far from the parents' workplace.
Parents use working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that a naturally loyal relationship is created here by an employee-employer.
Arch.Design has thus joined Czech companies offering significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program has strengthened personnel marketing.
The house is fascinated by the bone even after 100 years. Look into the interiors from Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
Such is the Casa Batlló house in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The house, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's Art Nouveau.
The facade of the house is played by dream lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In detailed observation, you can see the geometry, rhythm and precisely thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of the colors is even more enhanced.
Winding and twisting shapes with the same appearance in the interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and skirting boards.
House Batlló, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The renovation took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The apartment building Casa Batlló, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
It was co-operated with by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his designer plank that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of the mosaic on the facade.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started the successful collaboration of Jujola with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí’s house Casa Milá and Park Güell, in which there are other works of Gaudí.
From the locals, the house soon after completion earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others began to call it a "yawning house" because of the specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys for his time.
The bizarre may seem their forty-five-degree slope.
In the creation of Gaudí, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, during the completion, the city council was horrified by the result and asked for a remedy.
Councillors were annoyed, for example, that the building interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
The correction never took place, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the call of the city district, Josep Batlló applied (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house cuts through the staircase, which can be climbed up to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon door and the larger company can communicate with each other comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí’s reconstruction also received an unconventional roofing and two extra floors.
Also impressive is Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which are lined with an inner courtyard, and skylights.
The game of two colors adds maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
The Casa Batlló House, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house, the most spacious and spectacular apartment is made available to the public.
The owners decided for this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the hundred and 50th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed with the tours because they found out that it was a very advantageous enterprise and in addition extended the tours with common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20 percent discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of the house with dragon turrets, you need to quickly become friends with one of the residents of the apartment building and visit it directly at home.
