More and more parents want to monitor people, so they want to keep their children safe
Fear for their own child is driving more and more people to the idea of GPS-based guarding.
The system originally created for the search for cars can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help, for example, in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be big as a watch.
A number of people were frightened by the case of the missing Annie and began to look for means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about another means to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment for the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices may be misused, for example, if they put themselves in a bag to someone who doesn't know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Most of the time, customers actually buy it for safety reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in case of emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear anything similar, he will just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to lose some things on purpose when they don't want to be in control."
"Great expectations were previously raised by their parents, which can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková said.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"When it comes to the upcoming kidnapping, the perpetrator will practically always ensure that the child has no electronics with him that can reveal his location."
"It's the phone now."
"When the tracking devices start to expand, they will look for them, too, because their sales will certainly be backed by massive advertising."
"In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," the psychologist says.
However, it admits that a similar device can help in the event of a sudden infestation with a paedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after the attack, his presence can help.
"The device can be set to regularly send a location after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"More expensive devices have built-in and inclined meters, so even if a person just slips and stays motionless, the device immediately sends a warning with the position," says Čech.
According to him, a similar service can be done by smartphones with navigation, where it is enough to upload special software.
The problem with the current tracking units is that they are either devices similar to pendants the size of matches or smaller mobile phones.
There is always a risk of losing them.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, this is why a device that looks like a regular digital watch is now being tested.
