A longer index finger than a ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have a forename longer than a ring finger are at less risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is a surprising conclusion to a study published Wednesday by the British Cancer Journal.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly in combination with a genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burdens, Ms. Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 prostate cancer patients and, in parallel, over three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a forefinger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
It was the same probability of prostate cancer as for 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those who had a forefinger longer than the ring finger, this risk dropped by 33 percent, for men up to 60, the decrease was even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone matches a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone promotes growing prostate cancer.
A leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told the Czech News Agency that he was quick to know about the study, but he said it did not appear that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "completely proven".
