The promotion of democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the promotion of private enterprise.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered by many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current Latinobarometer survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can thus monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
Two related things dominate this year's survey, which took place in September and early October.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, democracy support has risen from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where economics was recovering after a deep decline in production last year.
But only around half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are convinced Democrats, which is pulling the regional average (see chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in their country in practice, this is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, this is a big increase (graph 3).
Roughly 34% said they trust the assembly in their country and 45% trust the government, again these are the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
A decade ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
Support arose during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission on Latin America announced this week that the ratio of Latinos living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
However, the mood is changing in a wide range from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a broadly accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and the state of violent crime deteriorated.
For only the second time since surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem (see chart 5).
Roughly 31% say that either they or their close relatives were victims of crime last year, but that's a drop compared to 38% from last year and is also the lowest number since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the area say private business is essential for development, this percentage increased from 56% from 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage grew from 47% from last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% support private business there), although their left-wing president Hugo Chavez expropriates many private firms.
Brazil is a country that has a leadership position in the region, as 19% of respondents mentioned (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, compared to last year unchanged) and Venezuela (9%, versus 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
