Microbes with resistance to arsenic increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the scope for searching for new forms of life on Earth and possibly beyond.
The researchers discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, claiming that it is a sign that life has options that stand outside the main elements that have so far been considered and essential.
"This organism has a dual capacity."
"It can grow either thanks to phosphorus or arsenic."
"This fact is very strange, but it is not proof that this is a form of truly 'alien' life," Paul C. said. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appeared Thursday in the online issue of the journal Science.
For a long time, it was considered necessary for life six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced by arsenic.
"It will start to amaze you for what is still possible," Ariel D said. Anbar from Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
This finding is significant for the search for life outside the Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life can look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on the news published to discuss it, which did not reveal the details of the find, prompted widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we consider to be 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't an accidental find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, which led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it exhibits high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she considered that the microbe, which is exposed to both elements, may be able to replace one after another.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"The result is that organisms can very hardly separate these elements from each other."
"However, the arsenic is so different that it doesn't work like phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic that bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better in the action of phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility is increased that the life-making form that uses arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic that could be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but there was never an example on which this fact could be proved.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it could have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health
