Without wanting to reduce the driving skills of the champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, or the possibilities of the Renault engine that drives his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula 1 - the "secret weapon" that the multi-ethnic Siemens put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful software simulating the marches that the German company launched in 2007 for the purposes of very distant automotive sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, was used to design assembly lines in production plants around the world, in energy plants and for devices with high accuracy.
It aims to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary errors and expenses.
The PLM has facilitated the development of the Canon camera, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains that the use of this software device has enabled the Red Bull team to carry out “in a few hours, in near-real time” modifications and improvements that are otherwise detected during races and trials.
Russwurm says that in 1992, stables employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to perform a maximum of three or four improvements over a period.
In the Red Bull team today, 180 young highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology are working to analyze and design each type of modification of racing vehicles.
A senior executive from Siemens explained that the PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull racing vehicles except the engine for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be converted from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production systems using lasers and highly technologically advanced autoclaves.
The only limit of this technical convenience is the amount of 40 million dollars representing the maximum that each Formula 1 team can issue for each period to improve their competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a high-tech plant to design and manufacture its racing cars, about 50 km from London.
These are two buildings that are restricted from entry to visits - especially journalists.
Everything that happens here is considered a “big secret.”
The list of participants in this project includes 580 people, including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The Red Bull hero is without a doubt the freshman champion Sebastian Vettel in Formula 1.
