Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel over her responsibility to start the current crisis.
How to interpret these movements?
Let it be said in advance that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here, Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is supposed to be, which alludes to the idea of following the old traditions held by a large part of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, there is speculation in Germany about three possible routes out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, while southern countries would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the mark - though it may now appear like a sci-fi, this version has widespread public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to Germany's proposals, is the recast of the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary rigour, fines for guilty states, possible postponement of payments for some of them, and with the extension of possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for the quizzes now.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission incited deficits in 2009, the German government pulled a constitutional reform from its sleeve to prevent it from 2016.
This was the first sign of the contradiction between what Germany considered to be correct (the fiscal rigour and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country when Merkel was painfully protracting the decision to save Greece.
Already then, it was the subject of sharp criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to Greece's rescue.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has reappeared with a clear position when she demanded to reform the European Union conventions so that a Member State can be rescued while making sure that private creditors are obliged to bear some of the costs.
This opinion was interpreted as anti-European because it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although in somewhat mitigated form, has been approved, and we should monitor the reform process of the Union within the next few months, which should allow these measures from 2013.
Germany has established a red line, which it does not intend to cross.
And he tells us all that, although now measures need to be taken that he seems to disagree with too much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will represent the birth of a new currency zone in which states infringing rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to report deferral of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear some of the costs.
Germany is suggesting that we must take a strict path of growth with an increase in savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital buffers.
A different option based on debt and building, with huge balance of payments gaps, which has reigned in the years of Spain's growth boom, simply do not intend to tolerate.
The offer is clear.
And we would have made a mistake if we didn't understand.
This is not just about restoring the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much tougher.
And the worst part is that under these conditions, we could be wrong about ourselves.
I hope that these current turbulences will replace more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunity they give us by spring 2013.
Prime Minister Zapatero seems to have understood this, too, and his double statement (the reforms promised after the meeting with the big businesses of last Saturday and yesterday's announcement of the new measures) gives an idea that despite critics in Merkel's address, the path has opened the way for the idea that things need to be put in order.
But the red line that Germany has set is there, and it does not appear to want to move it.
And from the possibilities that can be considered, leaving the eurozone full of not very serious countries can be excluded.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that it has warned us.
Sport and circumvention of the rules
The tricks, shown by Alonso and Ramos in the match against Ajax, show a wit not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged suspension of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on November 23 caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this was unsportsmanlike behaviour and whether, in turn, UEFA should not punish both footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team clearly won) the players named one by one deliberately wasted time when the foul was supposed to be played to provoke the judge, and he showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending up in their group in the lead - and will be able, stripped of their cards, to continue to the next stage.
In the end, the UEFA disciplinary committee gave coach Jose Mourinho a two-match penalty and the guilty players were given a monetary penalty.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but it is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, that is, rules that are unwritten, but follow.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that it was attended by the Real Madrid team (which boasts a nobleness and honor in its anthem, and which already fined its players for similar actions), and, it seems, also thanks to the dramatization led by Mourinho, which thus adds another episode to its long history of the comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of conduct, which is not explicitly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether there is a circumvention of the law in these deeds; these are indeed actions respecting sporting rules, the meaning of which, however, seems to be trying to circumvent.
It is discussed what type of damage such acts cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the requirements of sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opponents, which was not violated in these cases, i.e. there was no violent game.
Another of these essentials characterizing a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage over the opponent's team due to their offense - which also did not happen here.
Thus, paradoxical at the event of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as a trickery or circumvention of the law, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanction, but this behavior should have been as evident as possible in order to receive the punishment.
They waited and were happy to get the punishment.
The next question, however, is what advantage the culprits of their intentional offense will have.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that there will be no benefit in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And even that is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition to this action, the players will take the penalty, and will go to the second round of cards, in which one card less than in the first round is enough to exclude.
So how the rounds will continue will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow to get maximum benefit within the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid the punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or running away from punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumvention of the rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly a wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions were transmitted to their provocation from the management.
The damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
