The United States is changing the rules for granting visas
People will have to turn to the Visa Service Centers before interviewing the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
From January 10, 2011, the visa process will change to the United States Embassy and Consulates.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres (ASC in English) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The staff from the ASC will remove the applicant’s biometric information and will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer necessary to pay the fee for the appointment, the second for the processing of the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee, which shall cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with an application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and fingerprints will be taken away.
Since biometric information will be taken away in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra 26-dollar service fee.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
