The UN yesterday proposed a plan in Cancún to restore home lighting, lighting shops and industrial spaces in 100 countries in order to achieve a greenhouse effect restriction (GES) equivalent to almost one-third of the additional restrictions that need to be achieved to stabilize the planet's climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of large concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancun to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-reach commitments to reduce on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if hot bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market, replace the bulbs with flucompact or, even better, bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet created due to lighting would be degraded.
The lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
It's the equivalent of 70% of emissions from an auto park across the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to deduct 5 more Gt from this balance to achieve by 2020 the stabilisation of climate heating to 2 degrees Celsius in order to exclude that it will not get out of control.
In hot bulbs 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5% is the product of light.
